<span id="freeTextContainer15725539403109088317">I feel like I&apos;m one of the only people missing something here. I just finished a book about family, loyalty, dogs, and I just didn&apos;t get it. I didn&apos;t find myself connecting with the characters and as soon as I was starting to feel a connection (the last two hundred pages), Wroblewski throws out a half-baked ending leaving me saying, &quot;What?&quot;. I&apos;m not one that requires a tidy ending, but there should be some well-reasoned meaning. <br/><br/>(Please, Logan, no &quot;I told you so&quot; about Oprah.)</span>
  <span id="freeText15725539403109088317" style="display:none">I feel like I'm one of the only people missing something here. I just finished a book about family, loyalty, dogs, and I just didn't get it. I didn't find myself connecting with the characters and as soon as I was starting to feel a connection (the last two hundred pages), Wroblewski throws out a half-baked ending leaving me saying, "What?". I'm not one that requires a tidy ending, but there should be some well-reasoned meaning. <br /><br />(Please, Logan, no "I told you so" about Oprah.)</span>
