<span id="freeTextContainer14244262662309940464">I&apos;m re-reading Edgar Sawtelle for a book discussion next month on Constant Reader.<br/><br/>The Story of Edgar Sawtelle is a masterfully crafted tale, written in exquisite language that sets Wroblewski apart as a story teller and writer in his own right. At first I wanted to compare him to Steinbeck, but he belongs in a league of his own. If no one has ever had a dog, after finishing The Story of Edgar Sawtelle, I would venture to say you&apos;ll feel as though you&apos;ve had one all your life.</span>
  <span id="freeText14244262662309940464" style="display:none">I'm re-reading Edgar Sawtelle for a book discussion next month on Constant Reader.<br /><br />The Story of Edgar Sawtelle is a masterfully crafted tale, written in exquisite language that sets Wroblewski apart as a story teller and writer in his own right. At first I wanted to compare him to Steinbeck, but he belongs in a league of his own. If no one has ever had a dog, after finishing The Story of Edgar Sawtelle, I would venture to say you'll feel as though you've had one all your life.</span>
